The only lower molar available is an isolated m 1 (
Fig. 3
). It presents low and slightly inflated cusps. The trigonid is equivalent in length to the talonid. The protoconid is the tallest trigonid cusp. The metaconid is compressed labio-lingually and placed aligned transversally to protoconid. The paraconid is wide in its basis, with the apex not lingual but displaced labially. The trigonid presents a well-developed prefossid. The prefossid is anteriorly delimited by two short crests running from the apex of the paracone to the basis of the protoconid and of the metaconid. The talonid is wider than the trigonid. The entoconid is the tallest and largest cusp of the talonid, occupying much of the lingual margin of the talonid. The hypoconulid is small, twinned to the entoconid and slightly displaced labially in relation to it. The hypoconid is labially expanded and its basis is displaced posteriorly relative to the entoconid. The cristid obliqua ends anteriorly at a point labial to the posprotocristid notch. The anterior cingulid is narrow, and a short labial cingulid occurs in the postero-labial face of the protoconid.
